{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RXwBZ3xUAD7eemWR78pkm6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n3\tstatus: 'complete'\n4\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-02'\n5\tinputDocuments:\n6\t  - prd-evaluator-redesign.md\n7\t  - architecture-v2.md\n8\t  - research/domain-harness-design-long-running-agents-research-2026-04-01.md\n9\t  - research/technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md\n10\t---\n11\t\n12\t# codeharness v2 - Epic Breakdown\n13\t\n14\t## Overview\n15\t\n16\tThis document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for codeharness v2, decomposing 49 FRs, 18 NFRs, and 6 architectural decisions into implementable stories.\n17\t\n18\t## Requirements Inventory\n19\t\n20\t### Functional Requirements\n21\t\n22\t- FR1: User can define a workflow as a YAML file with tasks, flow order, and loop blocks\n23\t- FR2: User can specify per-task properties: agent assignment, scope, session boundary, source access, input/output contracts, prompt template\n24\t- FR3: User can define flow execution order as an ordered list of task references\n25\t- FR4: User can define loop steps using a loop: block containing an ordered list of tasks to repeat\n26\t- FR5: System validates workflow YAML against a JSON schema at parse time and rejects malformed definitions\n27\t- FR6: System ships a default embedded workflow for standard BMAD sprint execution\n28\t- FR7: System ships 9 embedded agents: dev, qa, architect, pm, sm, analyst, ux-designer, tech-writer, evaluator\n29\t- FR8: User can create custom agents at project level or user level\n30\t- FR9: User can patch embedded or user-level agents via extends with structured overrides and prompt_patches\n31\t- FR10: Agent config supports BMAD-compatible base fields and optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits\n32\t- FR11: System resolves agent config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n33\t- FR12: System compiles resolved agent config into Claude Code inline subagent definition\n34\t- FR13: User can create custom workflows at project level or user level\n35\t- FR14: User can patch embedded or user-level workflows via extends with structured overrides\n36\t- FR15: System resolves workflow config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n37\t- FR16: System reads resolved workflow and sprint-status.yaml to drive execution\n38\t- FR17: System executes per-story tasks once for each story in the sprint\n39\t- FR18: System executes per-run tasks once after all stories complete\n40\t- FR19: System dispatches agents via programmatic API with compiled subagent definitions\n41\t- FR20: System spawns fresh sessions or continues existing ones based on task session boundary config\n42\t- FR21: System passes defined input contracts to each task and collects defined outputs\n43\t- FR22: System generates a unique trace ID per iteration and injects it into agent prompts\n44\t- FR23: System enforces source_access: false by spawning the agent in a workspace with no source code\n45\t- FR24: System spawns a blind evaluator agent that exercises the built artifact via Docker and observability\n46\t- FR25: Evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently determines how to test each one\n47\t- FR26: Evaluator produces a structured JSON verdict with per-AC scores, status, evidence, findings\n48\t- FR27: Evaluator has access to story ACs, Docker container, observability — but not source code\n49\t- FR28: System re-verifies the entire artifact from scratch on each verification pass\n50\t- FR29: System injects evaluator findings into the retry task's agent prompt\n51\t- FR30: System filters retry execution to only stories the evaluator flagged as failed\n52\t- FR31: System executes flow loop steps until all ACs pass or circuit breaker triggers\n53\t- FR32: System tracks evaluator scores across iterations and detects score stagnation\n54\t- FR33: Circuit breaker triggers when evaluator scores stop improving\n55\t- FR34: System reports circuit breaker state with specific failures and score history\n56\t- FR35: User can resume execution after circuit breaker with manual fixes applied\n57\t- FR36: System generates and injects trace IDs that correlate across iteration, prompt, logs, metrics, traces\n58\t- FR37: Evaluator can query observability endpoints during verification\n59\t- FR38: User can create issues via codeharness issue create with optional priority and source\n60\t- FR39: System stores issues in issues.yaml with id, title, source, priority, status\n61\t- FR40: System reads both sprint-status.yaml and issues.yaml during workflow execution\n62\t- FR41: Issues use the same status values and execution path as stories\n63\t- FR42: Retro findings tagged as actionable are automatically added to issues.yaml\n64\t- FR43: User can run codeharness init to detect stack, generate default workflow, set up project\n65\t- FR44: User can run codeharness run to execute the workflow\n66\t- FR45: User can run codeharness validate to check workflow and agent YAML against schemas\n67\t- FR46: User can run codeharness status to see progress, evaluator scores, circuit breaker state\n68\t- FR47: User can run codeharness issue to create, list, and manage issues\n69\t- FR48: System does not contain Ralph bash loop, session flags, proof parsers, self-verify hooks, beads\n70\t- FR49: System has exactly one verification path: blind evaluator session\n71\t\n72\t### Non-Functional Requirements\n73\t\n74\t- NFR1: Workflow YAML parsing and validation in <500ms\n75\t- NFR2: Agent config resolution in <200ms\n76\t- NFR3: Agent session spawn in <5s excluding model response\n77\t- NFR4: Circuit breaker evaluation in <100ms\n78\t- NFR5: codeharness status returns in <1s\n79\t- NFR6: Engine state survives crashes — resume from last completed task\n80\t- NFR7: Evaluator timeout is scored failure, not fatal error\n81\t- NFR8: All state persisted after each task completion\n82\t- NFR9: Engine handles agent dispatch API errors gracefully\n83\t- NFR10: 4+ hour executions do not degrade or leak\n84\t- NFR11: Official programmatic agent dispatch API — no CLI spawning\n85\t- NFR12: BMAD agent configs read-only\n86\t- NFR13: Docker lifecycle managed by engine\n87\t- NFR14: Observability stack optional — graceful degradation\n88\t- NFR15: 80%+ unit test coverage on new modules\n89\t- NFR16: Zero shell scripts in execution path\n90\t- NFR17: Net negative LOC after legacy removal\n91\t- NFR18: Explicit TypeScript types, no any in API surface\n92\t\n93\t### Additional Requirements\n94\t\n95\t**From Architecture:**\n96\t- 7 modules in dependency order: workflow-state → workflow-parser → agent-resolver → agent-dispatch → workflow-engine → evaluator → circuit-breaker\n97\t- Evaluator workspace: temp dir, bare: true, disallowedTools: [Edit, Write]\n98\t- Embedded templates in templates/agents/ and templates/workflows/\n99\t- Config cached at startup\n100\t- Verdict enforced by JSON schema\n101\t- issues.yaml replaces beads\n102\t- 12 files need beads import cleanup\n103\t- ~40 files deleted (ralph/, hooks/, 8 lib, 3 templates)\n104\t- 13 commands reworked, 1 deleted, 3 kept\n105\t- 3 skills reworked, plugin.json updated\n106\t\n107\t**From Research:**\n108\t- Agent SDK query() as execution substrate\n109\t- loop: block syntax for flows\n110\t- BMAD → SDK inline subagent at runtime\n111\t- Evaluator judges subjectively, no contracts\n112\t- Anti-leniency: evidence per verdict\n113\t\n114\t### FR Coverage Map\n115\t\n116\t| FR | Epic | Description |\n117\t|----|------|-------------|\n118\t| FR1-6 | Epic 2 | Workflow definition, YAML schema, default workflow |\n119\t| FR7-12 | Epic 3 | Agent config, embedded agents, patching, resolution |\n120\t| FR13-15 | Epic 9 | Workflow config patching and resolution |\n121\t| FR16-18 | Epic 5 | Execution engine, per-story/per-run scope |\n122\t| FR19-23 | Epic 4 | Agent dispatch, sessions, trace IDs, source isolation |\n123\t| FR24-28 | Epic 6 | Blind evaluator, subjective verification, JSON verdict |\n124\t| FR29-31 | Epic 5 | Feedback loop, finding injection, loop execution |\n125\t| FR32-35 | Epic 7 | Circuit breaker, score stagnation, resume |\n126\t| FR36 | Epic 4 | Trace ID generation and injection |\n127\t| FR37 | Epic 6 | Evaluator observability queries |\n128\t| FR38-39, FR42 | Epic 8 | Issue create, store, retro auto-import |\n129\t| FR40-41 | Epic 5 | Engine reads issues.yaml alongside sprint-status |\n130\t| FR43 | Epic 2 | codeharness init |\n131\t| FR44 | Epic 5 | codeharness run |\n132\t| FR45 | Epic 2 | codeharness validate |\n133\t| FR46 | Epic 5 | codeharness status |\n134\t| FR47 | Epic 8 | codeharness issue |\n135\t| FR48-49 | Epic 1 | Legacy removal |\n136\t\n137\t## Epic List\n138\t\n139\t### Epic 1: Legacy Cleanup & Foundation\n140\tDeveloper has a clean codebase — beads removed, legacy files deleted, workflow-state module as foundation.\n141\t**FRs:** FR48, FR49 | **NFRs:** NFR16, NFR17\n142\t\n143\t### Epic 2: Workflow Definition & Validation\n144\tDeveloper can author workflow YAML, validate it, and init generates a default workflow.\n145\t**FRs:** FR1-6, FR43, FR45 | **NFRs:** NFR1\n146\t\n147\t### Epic 3: Agent Configuration System\n148\t9 embedded agents available. Custom agents and patches at project/user level. Config resolution chain.\n149\t**FRs:** FR7-12 | **NFRs:** NFR2, NFR12\n150\t\n151\t### Epic 4: Agent Dispatch & Session Management\n152\tEngine spawns Claude Code sessions via Agent SDK with session boundaries, trace IDs, and source isolation.\n153\t**FRs:** FR19-23, FR36 | **NFRs:** NFR3, NFR11\n154\t\n155\t### Epic 5: Workflow Execution Engine\n156\t`codeharness run` executes the workflow — per-story tasks, per-run tasks, loop blocks, finding injection. Reads stories and issues.\n157\t**FRs:** FR13-18, FR29-31, FR40-41, FR44, FR46 | **NFRs:** NFR6-10\n158\t\n159\t### Epic 6: Blind Evaluator & Verification\n160\tBlind evaluator exercises artifact, produces JSON verdict with per-AC evidence, engine handles retry loop.\n161\t**FRs:** FR24-28, FR37 | **NFRs:** NFR7, NFR13, NFR14\n162\t\n163\t### Epic 7: Circuit Breaker & Progress Detection\n164\tScore-based stagnation detection, halt on no-progress, specific failure reporting, resume after manual fixes.\n165\t**FRs:** FR32-35 | **NFRs:** NFR4\n166\t\n167\t### Epic 8: Issue Tracking & Retro Integration\n168\t`codeharness issue` CLI for create/list/manage. Retro findings auto-import. Issues execute alongside stories.\n169\t**FRs:** FR38-39, FR42, FR47\n170\t\n171\t### Epic 9: Workflow Configuration & Patching\n172\tCustom workflows or patches at project/user level. Changes without touching source.\n173\t**FRs:** FR13-15\n174\t\n175\t---\n176\t\n177\t## Epic 1: Legacy Cleanup & Foundation\n178\t\n179\tDeveloper has a clean codebase — beads removed, legacy files deleted, workflow-state module as foundation.\n180\t\n181\t### Story 1.1: Delete Beads Integration\n182\t\n183\tAs a developer,\n184\tI want all beads imports and calls removed from the codebase,\n185\tSo that I can build new features without dead dependency chains.\n186\t\n187\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n188\t\n189\t**Given** the current codebase has beads.ts and beads-sync.ts with 12+ dependent files\n190\t**When** beads.ts, beads-sync.ts, and all beads imports are removed\n191\t**Then** `npm run build` succeeds with zero beads references\n192\t**And** the 12 dependent files compile without beads imports\n193\t**And** `npm run test:unit` passes\n194\t\n195\t### Story 1.2: Delete Ralph Loop & Legacy Verification\n196\t\n197\tAs a developer,\n198\tI want the Ralph bash loop, old hooks, and proof document system deleted,\n199\tSo that only the new architecture's code paths exist.\n200\t\n201\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n202\t\n203\t**Given** ralph/ directory, hooks/ directory, and legacy lib modules exist\n204\t**When** all legacy files are deleted and their imports removed\n205\t**Then** ralph/ directory no longer exists\n206\t**And** hooks/ directory no longer exists\n207\t**And** src/lib/ does not contain verify.ts, verify-parser.ts, verifier-session.ts, patch-engine.ts, retry-state.ts, or old state.ts\n208\t**And** src/templates/ does not contain showboat-template.ts, verify-prompt.ts, or ralph-prompt.ts\n209\t**And** src/commands/retry.ts is deleted\n210\t**And** `npm run build` succeeds\n211\t**And** zero shell scripts remain in the execution path\n212\t\n213\t### Story 1.3: Workflow State Module\n214\t\n215\tAs a developer,\n216\tI want a workflow-state module that persists execution state to YAML,\n217\tSo that the engine can resume from the last completed task after a crash.\n218\t\n219\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n220\t\n221\t**Given** no workflow-state.yaml exists\n222\t**When** `writeState()` is called after a task completion\n223\t**Then** `.codeharness/workflow-state.yaml` is created with workflow name, started timestamp, iteration, phase, tasks_completed array, evaluator_scores array, and circuit_breaker state\n224\t**And** `readState()` returns the persisted state\n225\t**And** state survives process exit and is readable on restart\n226\t**And** unit tests cover read, write, crash recovery, and corrupted file handling at 80%+ coverage\n227\t\n228\t---\n229\t\n230\t## Epic 2: Workflow Definition & Validation\n231\t\n232\tDeveloper can author workflow YAML, validate it, and init generates a default.\n233\t\n234\t### Story 2.1: Workflow YAML JSON Schema\n235\t\n236\tAs a developer,\n237\tI want a JSON schema defining valid workflow YAML structure,\n238\tSo that malformed workflows are rejected at parse time.\n239\t\n240\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n241\t\n242\t**Given** a workflow YAML file\n243\t**When** validated against the JSON schema\n244\t**Then** valid workflows with tasks and flow pass validation\n245\t**And** missing required fields are rejected with specific errors\n246\t**And** invalid scope values are rejected\n247\t**And** loop: blocks with non-existent task references are rejected\n248\t**And** schema file exists at src/schemas/workflow.schema.json\n249\t\n250\t### Story 2.2: Workflow Parser Module\n251\t\n252\tAs a developer,\n253\tI want a workflow-parser module that loads, validates, and resolves workflow YAML,\n254\tSo that the engine receives a fully resolved config.\n255\t\n256\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n257\t\n258\t**Given** a workflow YAML file path\n259\t**When** `parseWorkflow()` is called\n260\t**Then** YAML is parsed and validated against the JSON schema\n261\t**And** invalid YAML returns a specific parse error\n262\t**And** parsing completes in <500ms\n263\t**And** returned object contains resolved tasks and flow with typed interfaces\n264\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n265\t\n266\t### Story 2.3: Default Embedded Workflow\n267\t\n268\tAs a developer,\n269\tI want a default workflow YAML shipped with codeharness,\n270\tSo that `codeharness run` works without custom configuration.\n271\t\n272\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n273\t\n274\t**Given** codeharness is installed\n275\t**When** the default workflow is loaded from templates/workflows/default.yaml\n276\t**Then** it defines implement, verify, and retry tasks with correct properties\n277\t**And** flow is: implement → verify → loop: [retry, verify]\n278\t**And** it validates against the JSON schema\n279\t\n280\t### Story 2.4: Init Command — Workflow Generation\n281\t\n282\tAs a developer,\n283\tI want `codeharness init` to generate a default workflow in my project,\n284\tSo that I can start using codeharness without manual setup.\n285\t\n286\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n287\t\n288\t**Given** a project without .codeharness/workflows/\n289\t**When** `codeharness init` runs\n290\t**Then** `.codeharness/workflows/default.yaml` is created from embedded template\n291\t**And** existing stack detection still works\n292\t**And** `--force` overwrites existing workflow files\n293\t\n294\t### Story 2.5: Validate Command\n295\t\n296\tAs a developer,\n297\tI want `codeharness validate` to check YAML files against schemas,\n298\tSo that I catch configuration errors before running.\n299\t\n300\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n301\t\n302\t**Given** workflow and agent YAML files in the project\n303\t**When** `codeharness validate` runs\n304\t**Then** all YAML files are validated against their schemas\n305\t**And** errors report file path, line context, and specific violation\n306\t**And** exit code 0 on success, 1 on failure\n307\t\n308\t---\n309\t\n310\t## Epic 3: Agent Configuration System\n311\t\n312\t9 embedded agents, custom agents, patching, config resolution chain.\n313\t\n314\t### Story 3.1: Agent Config JSON Schema\n315\t\n316\tAs a developer,\n317\tI want a JSON schema defining valid agent configuration,\n318\tSo that malformed agent configs are caught before dispatch.\n319\t\n320\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n321\t\n322\t**Given** an agent YAML file\n323\t**When** validated against the schema\n324\t**Then** valid configs with name, role, persona, and optional personality.traits pass\n325\t**And** missing required fields are rejected\n326\t**And** traits outside 0-1 range are rejected\n327\t**And** schema file exists at src/schemas/agent.schema.json\n328\t\n329\t### Story 3.2: Embedded Agent Templates\n330\t\n331\tAs a developer,\n332\tI want 9 agent YAML files shipped with codeharness,\n333\tSo that the default workflow has agents to dispatch.\n334\t\n335\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n336\t\n337\t**Given** codeharness is installed\n338\t**When** embedded agents are loaded from templates/agents/\n339\t**Then** 9 agents exist: dev, qa, architect, pm, sm, analyst, ux-designer, tech-writer, evaluator\n340\t**And** each has name, role, persona fields from BMAD definitions\n341\t**And** evaluator has anti-leniency principles and disallowedTools\n342\t**And** all 9 validate against the agent JSON schema\n343\t**And** BMAD agent configs are never modified\n344\t\n345\t### Story 3.3: Agent Resolver Module\n346\t\n347\tAs a developer,\n348\tI want an agent-resolver that resolves configs through the patch chain,\n349\tSo that customizations overlay cleanly on embedded defaults.\n350\t\n351\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n352\t\n353\t**Given** an embedded agent and optional user/project patches\n354\t**When** `resolveAgent(\"dev\")` is called\n355\t**Then** embedded config is loaded, user patch merged if exists, project patch merged on top\n356\t**And** resolved config is compiled into a Claude Code inline subagent definition\n357\t**And** resolution completes in <200ms\n358\t**And** missing patches silently skipped, malformed patches fail loud\n359\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n360\t\n361\t---\n362\t\n363\t## Epic 4: Agent Dispatch & Session Management\n364\t\n365\tEngine spawns Claude Code sessions via Agent SDK with session boundaries, trace IDs, source isolation.\n366\t\n367\t### Story 4.1: Agent Dispatch Module — SDK Integration\n368\t\n369\tAs a developer,\n370\tI want an agent-dispatch module that spawns sessions via the Agent SDK,\n371\tSo that agent execution is programmatic and reliable.\n372\t\n373\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n374\t\n375\t**Given** a compiled subagent definition and a prompt\n376\t**When** `dispatchAgent()` is called\n377\t**Then** Agent SDK `query()` is invoked with bare: true\n378\t**And** function returns when session completes\n379\t**And** spawn completes in <5s excluding model response\n380\t**And** no child_process.spawn used for Claude CLI\n381\t**And** API limit, network, and binary-not-found errors handled gracefully\n382\t\n383\t### Story 4.2: Session Boundary Management\n384\t\n385\tAs a developer,\n386\tI want session boundaries configurable per task,\n387\tSo that context resets and continuity are controlled.\n388\t\n389\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n390\t\n391\t**Given** a task with session: fresh\n392\t**When** dispatched\n393\t**Then** a new SDK query is created with no resume/continue\n394\t**And** given session: continue, previous session ID is passed via resume\n395\t**And** session IDs tracked in workflow-state\n396\t\n397\t### Story 4.3: Trace ID Generation & Injection\n398\t\n399\tAs a developer,\n400\tI want trace IDs generated per iteration and injected into prompts,\n401\tSo that agent activity correlates to observability data.\n402\t\n403\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n404\t\n405\t**Given** an iteration starting\n406\t**When** a trace ID is generated\n407\t**Then** format is `ch-{runId}-{iteration}-{taskName}`\n408\t**And** injected into agent's system prompt via appendSystemPrompt\n409\t**And** recorded in workflow-state.yaml\n410\t\n411\t### Story 4.4: Source Isolation Enforcement\n412\t\n413\tAs a developer,\n414\tI want source_access: false enforced via source-free workspace,\n415\tSo that the evaluator cannot access implementation code.\n416\t\n417\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n418\t\n419\t**Given** a task with source_access: false\n420\t**When** the agent is dispatched\n421\t**Then** temp directory created with only story files\n422\t**And** SDK cwd set to temp directory\n423\t**And** disallowedTools: [Edit, Write] set on subagent\n424\t**And** src/ not present in workspace\n425\t\n426\t---\n427\t\n428\t## Epic 5: Workflow Execution Engine\n429\t\n430\t`codeharness run` executes workflows — per-story, per-run, loop blocks, finding injection, reads stories and issues.\n431\t\n432\t### Story 5.1: Flow Execution — Sequential Steps\n433\t\n434\tAs a developer,\n435\tI want the engine to execute flow steps sequentially,\n436\tSo that tasks run in defined order.\n437\t\n438\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n439\t\n440\t**Given** a resolved workflow with flow: [implement, verify]\n441\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n442\t**Then** per-story tasks run first (one per story/issue)\n443\t**And** per-run tasks run once after\n444\t**And** workflow-state updated after each task\n445\t**And** engine reads both sprint-status.yaml and issues.yaml\n446\t\n447\t### Story 5.2: Flow Execution — Loop Blocks\n448\t\n449\tAs a developer,\n450\tI want loop: blocks to repeat until pass or circuit breaker,\n451\tSo that retry cycles are automatic.\n452\t\n453\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n454\t\n455\t**Given** flow with loop: [retry, verify]\n456\t**When** verify produces non-passing verdict\n457\t**Then** retry runs for failed stories only with findings injected\n458\t**And** verify re-runs entire artifact from scratch\n459\t**And** loop repeats until all pass or max iterations\n460\t**And** each iteration recorded in workflow-state\n461\t\n462\t### Story 5.3: Crash Recovery & Resume\n463\t\n464\tAs a developer,\n465\tI want the engine to resume from last completed task after crash,\n466\tSo that long-running executions don't lose progress.\n467\t\n468\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n469\t\n470\t**Given** workflow-state shows tasks completed up to a checkpoint\n471\t**When** `codeharness run` or `--resume` starts\n472\t**Then** engine skips completed tasks, resumes from next\n473\t**And** no task executed twice\n474\t**And** 4+ hour executions don't degrade or leak\n475\t\n476\t### Story 5.4: Run & Status Commands\n477\t\n478\tAs a developer,\n479\tI want `codeharness run` and `codeharness status` to work,\n480\tSo that I can execute workflows and monitor progress.\n481\t\n482\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n483\t\n484\t**Given** a project with resolved workflow and sprint-status.yaml\n485\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n486\t**Then** workflow engine is invoked\n487\t**And** `codeharness status` shows iteration, stories, scores, circuit breaker, elapsed time\n488\t**And** status returns in <1s\n489\t\n490\t---\n491\t\n492\t## Epic 6: Blind Evaluator & Verification\n493\t\n494\tBlind evaluator exercises artifact, produces JSON verdict, engine handles retry loop.\n495\t\n496\t### Story 6.1: Evaluator Module — Workspace & Spawn\n497\t\n498\tAs a developer,\n499\tI want an evaluator module that sets up source-free workspace and spawns the evaluator,\n500\tSo that verification is truly blind.\n501\t\n502\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n503\t\n504\t**Given** all stories are implemented\n505\t**When** evaluator task runs\n506\t**Then** temp workspace created with AC files and Docker access, no source\n507\t**And** evaluator spawned via agent-dispatch with bare: true, source_access: false\n508\t**And** Docker lifecycle managed by engine\n509\t**And** if Docker not running, verdict is all UNKNOWN with finding\n510\t**And** timeout produces scored UNKNOWN, not fatal error\n511\t\n512\t### Story 6.2: Evaluator Verdict JSON Schema & Parsing\n513\t\n514\tAs a developer,\n515\tI want the evaluator to produce structured JSON validated by schema,\n516\tSo that every AC has status and evidence.\n517\t\n518\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n519\t\n520\t**Given** evaluator completes its session\n521\t**When** output is parsed\n522\t**Then** conforms to verdict schema: verdict, score, findings with per-AC status and evidence\n523\t**And** invalid JSON triggers one retry, then all UNKNOWN\n524\t**And** schema at src/schemas/verdict.schema.json\n525\t**And** every PASS has non-empty evidence.commands_run\n526\t\n527\t### Story 6.3: Evaluator Prompt Template\n528\t\n529\tAs a developer,\n530\tI want the evaluator agent YAML to include anti-leniency instructions,\n531\tSo that the evaluator requires evidence for every verdict.\n532\t\n533\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n534\t\n535\t**Given** evaluator loaded from templates/agents/evaluator.yaml\n536\t**When** compiled to subagent definition\n537\t**Then** prompt instructs: read ACs, independently test, evidence for every PASS, UNKNOWN if can't verify, never benefit of the doubt\n538\t**And** evaluator can query observability endpoints\n539\t\n540\t---\n541\t\n542\t## Epic 7: Circuit Breaker & Progress Detection\n543\t\n544\tScore-based stagnation detection, halt, reporting, resume.\n545\t\n546\t### Story 7.1: Score-Based Circuit Breaker Module\n547\t\n548\tAs a developer,\n549\tI want a circuit breaker that detects evaluator score stagnation,\n550\tSo that the engine halts instead of burning tokens.\n551\t\n552\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n553\t\n554\t**Given** evaluator scores across iterations\n555\t**When** `evaluateProgress()` called after each verify\n556\t**Then** stagnation detected when scores don't improve\n557\t**And** returns halt with remaining failures and score history\n558\t**And** evaluation in <100ms\n559\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n560\t\n561\t### Story 7.2: Resume After Circuit Breaker\n562\t\n563\tAs a developer,\n564\tI want to resume after circuit breaker halts,\n565\tSo that I can apply manual fixes and re-run.\n566\t\n567\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n568\t\n569\t**Given** circuit breaker has halted\n570\t**When** `codeharness run --resume` executes\n571\t**Then** engine reads state, resets circuit breaker for current iteration\n572\t**And** resumes from verify step\n573\t**And** previous findings available in state\n574\t\n575\t---\n576\t\n577\t## Epic 8: Issue Tracking & Retro Integration\n578\t\n579\t`codeharness issue` CLI, retro auto-import, issues execute alongside stories.\n580\t\n581\t### Story 8.1: Issue Tracker Module & CLI\n582\t\n583\tAs a developer,\n584\tI want to create, list, and manage issues via `codeharness issue`,\n585\tSo that bugs and tech debt have a path to implementation.\n586\t\n587\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n588\t\n589\t**Given** no issues.yaml exists\n590\t**When** `codeharness issue create \"Fix Docker timeout\" --priority high --source retro-sprint-1` runs\n591\t**Then** issues.yaml created with auto-generated id, title, source, priority, status: backlog\n592\t**And** `codeharness issue list` shows all issues\n593\t**And** `codeharness issue close issue-001` updates status to done\n594\t**And** same status values as sprint-status.yaml\n595\t\n596\t### Story 8.2: Retro Finding Auto-Import\n597\t\n598\tAs a developer,\n599\tI want retro findings tagged as actionable to appear in issues.yaml,\n600\tSo that action items don't rot in markdown.\n601\t\n602\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n603\t\n604\t**Given** a retrospective file with actionable findings\n605\t**When** `codeharness retro-import` runs\n606\t**Then** actionable findings added to issues.yaml with retro source\n607\t**And** duplicate detection prevents re-importing\n608\t**And** non-actionable findings ignored\n609\t\n610\t---\n611\t\n612\t## Epic 9: Workflow Configuration & Patching\n613\t\n614\tCustom workflows or patches at project/user level.\n615\t\n616\t### Story 9.1: Workflow Patch Resolution\n617\t\n618\tAs a developer,\n619\tI want to patch the default workflow via a patch file,\n620\tSo that I can customize execution without replacing the entire workflow.\n621\t\n622\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n623\t\n624\t**Given** embedded default workflow and project-level patch with extends: embedded://default\n625\t**When** workflow parser resolves\n626\t**Then** structured overrides merged onto embedded base\n627\t**And** replace overrides replace entire sections\n628\t**And** missing patches silently skipped\n629\t**And** malformed patches fail loud\n630\t**And** user-level patches applied before project-level\n631\t\n632\t### Story 9.2: Custom Workflow Creation\n633\t\n634\tAs a developer,\n635\tI want to create a custom workflow YAML in my project,\n636\tSo that I can define non-standard execution flows.\n637\t\n638\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n639\t\n640\t**Given** custom workflow at .codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml\n641\t**When** `codeharness run --workflow my-workflow` executes\n642\t**Then** custom workflow loaded, validated, and executed\n643\t**And** must pass JSON schema validation\n644\t**And** agent references resolve through same config chain\n645\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XScTPWbxkcynzQq2rGASAG","session_id":"c54cfa66-957c-4f2c-a205-da1113d93a9b","uuid":"9ecd889f-6821-4aa4-b11d-bb3671f48eea","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:03:21.142Z"}
