{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018PnUs2R5x4rKrqdevtPnuL","type":"tool_result","content":"99:1. Workflow YAML parser with JSON schema validation\n141:Alex has a BMAD sprint plan with 8 stories for a Node.js API. Runs `codeharness init`, then `codeharness run`. No workflow YAML to write — the default handles it.\n208:2. \"Good: workflow YAML was easy to customize\" (not actionable)\n232:Engine reads workflow YAML (resolved through embedded → user → project patches) and sprint-status.yaml:\n253:The workflow YAML is the primary API surface:\n254:- Formally specified with a JSON schema\n329:- FR1: User can define a workflow as a YAML file with tasks, flow order, and loop blocks\n330:- FR2: User can specify per-task properties: agent assignment, scope (per-story/per-run), session boundary (fresh/continue), source access, input/output contracts, and prompt template\n331:- FR3: User can define flow execution order as an ordered list of task references\n332:- FR4: User can define loop steps in the flow using a `loop:` block containing an ordered list of tasks to repeat\n333:- FR5: System validates workflow YAML against a JSON schema at parse time and rejects malformed definitions\n334:- FR6: System ships a default embedded workflow that handles standard BMAD sprint execution without user customization\n341:- FR10: Agent config supports BMAD-compatible base fields (name, role, persona with identity/communication_style/principles) and optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits (10 dimensions, 0-1 scale)\n342:- FR11: System resolves agent config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n343:- FR12: System compiles resolved agent config into Claude Code inline subagent definition for SDK dispatch\n347:- FR13: User can create custom workflows at project level (`.codeharness/workflows/`) or user level (`~/.codeharness/workflows/`)\n348:- FR14: User can patch embedded or user-level workflows via `extends:` with structured `overrides:`\n349:- FR15: System resolves workflow config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n353:- FR16: System reads resolved workflow and sprint-status.yaml to drive execution\n354:- FR17: System executes `per-story` tasks once for each story in the sprint\n355:- FR18: System executes `per-run` tasks once after all stories in the current phase complete\n356:- FR19: System dispatches agents via programmatic API with compiled subagent definitions\n357:- FR20: System spawns fresh sessions or continues existing ones based on task session boundary config\n358:- FR21: System passes defined input contracts to each task and collects defined outputs\n359:- FR22: System generates a unique trace ID per iteration and injects it into agent prompts\n360:- FR23: System enforces `source_access: false` by spawning the agent in a workspace with no source code\n364:- FR24: System spawns a blind evaluator agent that independently exercises the built artifact via Docker and observability endpoints\n365:- FR25: Evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently determines how to test each one — without access to implementation-specific test scripts, prior evaluator sessions, or source code\n366:- FR26: Evaluator produces a structured JSON verdict with per-AC scores, status (pass/fail/unknown), evidence (commands run, output observed), and specific findings for failures\n367:- FR27: Evaluator has access to story acceptance criteria, Docker container, and observability endpoints — but not source code\n368:- FR28: System re-verifies the entire artifact from scratch on each verification pass (no incremental verification)\n372:- FR29: System injects evaluator findings (specific per-AC failure details with evidence) into the retry task's agent prompt\n373:- FR30: System filters retry execution to only the stories the evaluator flagged as failed\n374:- FR31: System executes flow loop steps until all ACs pass or circuit breaker triggers\n378:- FR32: System tracks evaluator scores across iterations and detects score stagnation\n379:- FR33: Circuit breaker triggers when evaluator scores stop improving across consecutive iterations\n380:- FR34: System reports circuit breaker state with specific remaining failures and score history\n381:- FR35: User can resume execution after circuit breaker with manual fixes applied\n385:- FR36: System generates and injects trace IDs that correlate across iteration → agent prompt → logs → metrics → traces\n386:- FR37: Evaluator can query observability endpoints (VictoriaLogs, VictoriaMetrics, VictoriaTraces) during verification\n390:- FR38: User can create issues via `codeharness issue create \"title\"` with optional priority and source\n391:- FR39: System stores issues in `issues.yaml` with id, title, source, priority, and status\n392:- FR40: System reads both `sprint-status.yaml` (stories) and `issues.yaml` (issues) during workflow execution\n393:- FR41: Issues use the same status values and execution path as stories — the engine treats them uniformly\n394:- FR42: Retro workflow findings tagged as actionable are automatically added to issues.yaml\n398:- FR43: User can run `codeharness init` to detect stack, generate default workflow, and set up the project\n399:- FR44: User can run `codeharness run` to execute the workflow\n400:- FR45: User can run `codeharness validate` to check workflow and agent YAML against schemas\n401:- FR46: User can run `codeharness status` to see execution progress, evaluator scores, and circuit breaker state\n402:- FR47: User can run `codeharness issue` to create, list, and manage issues\n\n[Showing results with pagination = limit: 50]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XScTPWbxkcynzQq2rGASAG","session_id":"c54cfa66-957c-4f2c-a205-da1113d93a9b","uuid":"b39144fa-2e9f-4a93-9bfb-d48d31197dba","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:03:43.095Z"}
