{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XScTPWbxkcynzQq2rGASAG","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/2-1-workflow-yaml-json-schema.md`.\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 2.1\n- Story Key: 2-1-workflow-yaml-json-schema\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n- File: `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/2-1-workflow-yaml-json-schema.md`\n\n**What was done:**\n- Auto-discovered `2-1-workflow-yaml-json-schema` as the first backlog story from sprint-status.yaml\n- Loaded and analyzed: epics-v2.md, architecture-v2.md, prd-evaluator-redesign.md, previous story 1-3-workflow-state-module.md\n- Created comprehensive story file with 10 ACs, all tagged with verification tiers (all `test-provable`)\n- Included dev notes covering: schema shape from PRD, scope boundaries, ajv dependency decision, TypeScript interfaces, flow array heterogeneous item schema, downstream module needs, testing standards\n- Did NOT modify sprint-status.yaml per user instruction\n- Did NOT run git add/commit per user instruction\n\n**Note:** Sprint-status.yaml still shows `2-1-workflow-yaml-json-schema: backlog` and `epic-2: backlog`. Per workflow step 6, these should be updated to `ready-for-dev` and `in-progress` respectively, but user instruction forbids modifying sprint-status.yaml.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- The workflow references `_bmad/bmm/config.yaml` for variable resolution, but that file does not exist. Worked around by reading config values (planning_artifacts, implementation_artifacts paths) directly from the workflow.yaml and sprint-status.yaml locations.\n- The workflow engine research document (`technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md`) referenced in epics-v2.md inputDocuments does not exist locally. Not critical -- PRD and architecture provided sufficient detail for the schema shape.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- Inferred `planning_artifacts` and `implementation_artifacts` paths from existing file locations rather than config.yaml.\n- Skipped web research step (workflow step 4) since the technologies involved (JSON Schema, ajv, vitest) are well-known and stable. No version-critical information needed.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The `ajv` dependency recommendation is a judgment call. If the dev agent decides to use a hand-written validator instead, all ACs still pass -- the schema file is the primary deliverable.\n- AC #6 explicitly defers referential integrity (loop task names matching `tasks` keys) to story 2.2. If the dev agent misunderstands and tries to enforce it in the schema, it will over-scope.\n- The `flow` array `loop:` block YAML representation (`- loop:` with nested list) has a known YAML parsing nuance -- in YAML, `- loop:` followed by `- retry` creates `[{loop: null}, \"retry\"]` not `[{loop: [\"retry\"]}]`. The correct YAML is `- loop:\\n    - retry\\n    - verify`. The schema handles the parsed JSON form correctly but the dev should be aware of this YAML indentation sensitivity.\n\n**Observations:**\n- All 10 ACs are `test-provable` -- this story is pure schema definition and validation logic with no runtime requirements.\n- The `src/schemas/` directory is brand new. The dev agent needs to create it.\n- The previous story file (1-3) is well-structured and provides a good template for the dev agent to follow in terms of code patterns.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 22\n- By tool: Bash: 5, Read: 8, Grep: 5, Glob: 5, Write: 1, Skill: 1\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls implementation-artifacts/` (~165 lines), `ls __tests__/ | tail` (~15 lines), `git log` (~5 lines)\n- Files read: 10 unique, 10 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: none detected -- each read targeted a different file or section"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a70f4fc09e876ebca (use SendMessage with to: 'a70f4fc09e876ebca' to c